(40, 23, 15, 44, 13, 43, 43, 'proselyte', 'Proselytes and Their Influence', 'This connection highlights the theme of proselytes in both passages. In Matthew, the emphasis is on the negative impact of making a proselyte, while in Acts, the focus is on the positive influence of proselytes following Paul and Barnabas.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 23, 15, 49, 2, 3, 3, 'child of hell', 'Children of Wrath and Hell', 'This connection highlights the transformation of individuals into ''children'' of a negative state. Matthew speaks of making a proselyte ''twofold more the child of hell,'' while Ephesians describes being ''children of wrath.'' Both passages emphasize the consequences of spiritual influence.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 23, 15, 43, 8, 44, 44, 'twofold more the child of hell', 'Hypocrisy and Spiritual Deception', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of leading others astray. In Matthew, the scribes and Pharisees create proselytes who are worse off, while in John, Jesus identifies the Pharisees as children of the devil, highlighting their role in perpetuating lies.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
